Fig. 3. (de) Nomograms for predicting the probability of patient mortality based on TMRS-RFS (d), TMRS-OS (e) and clinical variables; (fg) Plots depict the calibration of nomograms based on TMRS-RFS (f) and TMRS-OS (g) in terms of agreement between predicted and observed 2-year, 3-year, and 5-year outcomes. Nomogram performance is shown by the plot, relative to the 45-degree line, which represents the ideal prediction; (hi) Decision curve analyses of the nomograms based on TMRS-RFS (h) and TMRS-OS (i) for 2-year, 3-year, and 5-year risk. ADJC, adjuvant chemotherapy; TMRS, tumour microenvironment risk score; RFS, relapse-free survival; OS, overall survival; Pr, probability; Nomo, nomogram.

The c forest plot can be drawn by referring to FigureYa90subgroup, and the h and i plots can be drawn by referring to FigureYa33DCA_update.

Application scenario

nomogram

LogisticCox

A nomogram is a graph that represents a functional relationship between multiple independent variables in a plane rectangular coordinate system using a cluster of disjointed line segments.

It visualizes the results of a Logistic regression or Cox regression, giving the risk or proportional risk of developing a disease.

surv4 <- function(x) surv(2920,x)

x <- nomogram(coxpbc,fun = list(surv3,surv4),lp=T,
            funlabel = c('5-year survival Probability','8-year survival Probability'),
            maxscale = 100,fun.at = c(0.95,0.9,0.8,0.7,0.6,0.5,0.4,0.3,0.2,0.1))

pdf("nomogram_classical.pdf",width = 12,height = 10)
plot(x, lplabel="Linear Predictor",
     xfrac=.35,varname.label=TRUE, varname.label.sep="=", ia.space=.2, 
     tck=NA, tcl=-0.20, lmgp=0.3,
     points.label='Points', total.points.label='Total Points',
     total.sep.page=FALSE, 
     cap.labels=FALSE,cex.var = 1.6,cex.axis = 1.05,lwd=5,
     label.every = 1,col.grid = gray(c(0.8, 0.95)))
dev.off()

nomogram

Draw new nomogram

regplotnomogram

regplotConsolePlots

EscEsc

ExportSave as PDFPDF

regplot can interactively adjust the nomogram, the code is simpler, the output graph is more beautiful.

Paste the code regplot into Console, enter, then the interactive plot will appear in the Plots window.

You can exit the interactive mode by clicking Esc or pressing Esc on the keyboard.

How do I save a picture?

Click on the small triangle on the right side of Export, Save as PDF The image will be saved as a PDF file.

pbccox <- coxph(formula = Surv(time,died) ~  age + catbili + sex + 
                   copper + stage + trt , data = pbc)

regplot(pbccox,
        observation=pbc[2,], #2 the six indicators for Observation 2 can be scored and displayed on the nomogram, or they may not be displayed.
        points = TRUE, #FALSEx 0-100  If FALSE the regression scores of each x contribution are shown. Otherwise contributions are represented by a 0-100 "points" scale.
        plots = c("density", #"no plot" "density" "boxes" "ecdf" "bars" "boxplot" "violin" "bean" "spikes" optional "no plot" "density" "boxes" "ecdf" "bars" "boxplot" "violin" "bean" "spikes"
                  "boxes"), #"no plot" "boxes" "bars" "spikes" optional "no plot" "boxes" "bars" "spikes"
        failtime = c(1095,1825), #35day predict the risk of death over 3 and 5 years, with the unit being days.
        subticks = TRUE, 
        #clickable=TRUE, # use the mouse to click
        prfail = TRUE, #coxTRUE TRUE is required in cox regression
        showP = T, # whether to demonstrate statistical differences
        droplines = F,#2 Observation 2 example scoring whether or not to draw a line
        rank="range", #rank=range xrank=sd x rank="range" is by the range of the x's, and rank="sd" is by the standard deviation of the x's. 
        interval="confidence") # demonstrate confidence intervals for observations

calibration curve

Plot calibration curve for validation

nomogramcox

Perform multivariable Cox regression using the same variables as the nomogram

5

5 years

f5 <- cph(formula = Surv(time,died) ~  age + catbili + sex + copper +stage + trt,data=pbc,x=T,y=T,surv = T,na.action=na.delete,time.inc = 1825) 

#m=5050
#the parameter m=50 means 50 samples in each group for repeated calculations
cal5 <- calibrate(f5, cmethod="KM", method="boot",u=1825,m=50,B=1000) 
## Using Cox survival estimates at 1825 Days
pdf("calibration_5y.pdf",width = 8,height = 8)
plot(cal5,
     lwd = 2,#error bar thickness of the error bar
     lty = 1,#error bar0-6 type of the error bar, which can be 0-6.
     errbar.col = c("#2166AC"),#error bar color of the error bar
     xlim = c(0,1),ylim= c(0,1),
     xlab = "Nomogram-prediced OS (%)",ylab = "Observed OS (%)",
     cex.lab=1.2, cex.axis=1, cex.main=1.2, cex.sub=0.6) # font size
lines(cal5[,c('mean.predicted',"KM")], 
      type = 'b', #"p","b","o" type of line, which can be p, b, o.
      lwd = 2, # thickness of the line
      pch = 16, #0-20 shape of the point, which can be 0-20
      col = c("#2166AC")) # color of the line
mtext("")
box(lwd = 1) # border thickness
abline(0,1,lty = 3, # diagonal lines are dashed
       lwd = 2, # diagonal thickness
       col = c("#224444")# diagonal color
       ) 
dev.off()
## png 
##   2

f8 <- cph(formula = Surv(time,died) ~  age + catbili + sex + copper +stage + trt,data=pbc,x=T,y=T,surv = T,na.action=na.delete,time.inc = 2920) 
cal8 <- calibrate(f8, cmethod="KM", method="boot",u=2920,m=50,B=1000)
## Using Cox survival estimates at 2920 Days
plot(cal8,
     lwd = 2,
     lty = 1,
     errbar.col = c("#B2182B"),
     xlim = c(0,1),ylim= c(0,1),
     xlab = "Nomogram-prediced OS (%)",ylab = "Observed OS (%)",
     col = c("#B2182B"),
     cex.lab=1.2,cex.axis=1, cex.main=1.2, cex.sub=0.6)
lines(cal8[,c('mean.predicted',"KM")],
      type= 'b',
      lwd = 2,
      col = c("#B2182B"),
      pch = 16)
mtext("")
box(lwd = 1)
abline(0,1,lty= 3,
       lwd = 2,
       col =c("#224444"))

curve

Show two curves at the same time

pdf("calibration_compare.pdf",width = 8,height = 8)
plot(cal5,lwd = 2,lty = 0,errbar.col = c("#2166AC"),
     bty = "l", # draw only the left and lower borders
     xlim = c(0,1),ylim= c(0,1),
     xlab = "Nomogram-prediced OS (%)",ylab = "Observed OS (%)",
     col = c("#2166AC"),
     cex.lab=1.2,cex.axis=1, cex.main=1.2, cex.sub=0.6)
lines(cal5[,c('mean.predicted',"KM")],
      type = 'b', lwd = 1, col = c("#2166AC"), pch = 16)
mtext("")

plot(cal8,lwd = 2,lty = 0,errbar.col = c("#B2182B"),
     xlim = c(0,1),ylim= c(0,1),col = c("#B2182B"),add = T)
lines(cal8[,c('mean.predicted',"KM")],
      type = 'b', lwd = 1, col = c("#B2182B"), pch = 16)

abline(0,1, lwd = 2, lty = 3, col = c("#224444"))

legend("topleft", # location of the legend
       legend = c("5-year","8-year"), # legend text
       col =c("#2166AC","#B2182B"), # color of the legend line, corresponding to the text
       lwd = 2,# thickness of lines in the legend
       cex = 1.2,# legend font size
       bty = "n")# legend border not displayed
dev.off()
